An American-style crony capitalism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the US Department of the Treasury and its IMF allies blamed the problems of this region on crony capitalism, a lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting control offices, to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them to manage their businesses.
Regardless of whether under its own entrepreneurs' authority, East Asia developed more rapidly than any other region - and with greater stability - over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal lends new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "One must be faultless to criticize others".
Enron used large accounting schemes and complex financial products (derivatives) to deceive investors about its value.
No transparency here.
She used her money to acquire influence and power, shape the US energy policy and exempt themselves from regulations.
Favoritism capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of a single party.
The former US Secretary of the Treasury, Robert Rubin, may have attempted to influence the current government to intervene on behalf of Enron in the contentious dispute in India.
When in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards-setting board attempted to clean up the accounts of high-ranking officials at a premium.
It's in part thanks to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent has been hindered.
America's enthusiasm to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the free market ideology is merely a thin veil for the well-being of old companies: giving to those with the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and the problems were not revealed is a testament to the absence of favorable capitalism.
My interpretation is different: this shows the importance of a free press that can't stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to focus on Enron, the number of Congressional members who had accepted Enron money was disclosed.
Contributions to campaigns did not simply relate to public interest, but constituted an investment.
As with most of Enron's investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be learned from this venture.
Some concerning politics: the Enron scandal reinforces the arguments in favor of reforming campaign financing and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests that can in fact buy elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to disclose information that would confirm the role of corporate interests in defining its energy policy.
Other lessons cover economics, especially information economics.
For markets to function, for the right signals to be provided in order to efficiently allocate resources, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
The control of accounts is intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guards ?
Who will control the accountants' controllers ?
We count a great deal on the motivations.
Independent auditors want to preserve their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory services and accounting audits also brings other perverted motivations : a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: Given that many within auditing firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of the audits could be compromised.
It is no doubt the unsung hero of the debacle.
But audit firms and their corporate clients - which is not surprising, given the backlash that developed - strongly attacked his proposal to separate consulting and audit activities.
What Levitt understood - and the Enron debacle has so clearly shown - is that motivations are important, but unbridled markets cannot themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for wealth creation; they can provide motivations for the kind of combinations that Enron was operating.
The new economy - and its new complex financial instruments - highlights the problems of reliable accounting control structures; it makes them easier to obfuscate.
Rather than facing problems, corporate America systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by good old-fashioned American crony capitalism.
The major problem of our times is finding the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will affirm that Enron was an exception: that its collapse was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud and that those who violate these laws must suffer the consequences and will suffer them.
But most of Enron's actions were legal.
His auditors claim that his central practices conformed to the law and that thousands of companies act the same way.
They are right - and that's exactly the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received is sufficient to reflect the company's economic situation.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these guarantees at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Even though we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can attempt to inculcate better ethical standards.
But we can't count on them when so many people around the world don't even bat an eyelid at the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we notice that they can manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes apparent, new sites of abuse are created repeatedly – take the American repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investments.
We have on several occasions observed the consequences of the excesses of unbridled market releases.
We must now resist the temptation of leaning towards the other extreme.
The challenge to be met lies in achieving the right balance.
